fields.name: Allium
fields.description: Most commonly seen with graphic lollipop sihouettes, these garic cousins add explosive firework texture to arrangements.

fields.name: Amaryllis
fields.description: This focal flower is characterized by star-shaped blooms that flare out in a cluster atop a long, smooth stem.

fields.name: Artichoke
fields.description: Though mainly appreciated as a culinary delight, the artichoke can be an architectural wonder in a flower arrangement.

fields.name: Astilbe
fields.description: Spires of fluffy flowers, shaped like feathery plumes, add dramatic vertical accents to arrangements.

fields.name: Bells of Ireland
fields.description: Florists love bells of Ireland for their availability and longevity, and you’ll see them used in wedding flower arrangements as often as in St. Patrick’s day bouquets.

fields.name: Calla Lily
fields.description: The smooth, clean lines of this classic bloom seem to have sprung from a sculptor's hands.

fields.name: Carnation
fields.description: Although they are often seen in uninspiring mixed supermarket bunches and funeral arrangements, these durable and long-lasting blooms are making a comeback.

fields.name: Chrysanthemum
fields.description: Pompon, quill, spider, and spoon are just a few of the fascinating forms of the chrysanthemum flower.

fields.name: Cosmos
fields.description: Spell "summer" another way and you get cosmos, the cheerful flower with soft, feathery foliage.

fields.name: Dahlia
fields.description: Dahlias come in an endless array of sizes, shapes, and astonishingly vivid colors.

fields.name: Delphinium
fields.description: These tall flowers open from the bottom up, so pick stems that have open blossoms only halfway up for the longest bloom time.

fields.name: Hyacinth
fields.description: These fragrant spring bulbs are easily forced even when indoors, and their bright white roots look stunning when displayed in clear glass.

fields.name: Hydrangea
fields.description: The cotton-candy-like clusters of hydrangea make it an ideal base to feed other flowers through in an arrangement.

fields.name: Hypericum Berry
fields.description: More commonly known as Saint-John's-wort, hypericum flowers bloom yellow with a pincushionlike center.

fields.name: Kale
fields.description: Most of us are used to seeing kale on our dinner plates, but this surprisingly colorful vegetable can bring depth and texture to flower arrangements.

fields.name: Lavender
fields.description: Lavender's silvery foliage and spiky blossoms bring both form and fragrance to arrangements.

fields.name: Lily
fields.description: Tall and powerful, the lily is a true superstar of the flower world.

fields.name: Lisianthus
fields.description: Despite its delicate appearance, lisanthus is a tough little flower that thrives in the hot grasshands of the United States and Mexico.

fields.name: Lupine
fields.description: These bright wildflowers turn spring hillsides into blankets of blue or yellow, while the hybrid varieties from giant, colorful spires that are perfect for focal arrangements.

fields.name: Orchid
fields.description: With more than twenty thousand different species, orchids are memebers of one of the largest families in the plant kingdom.

fields.name: Peony
fields.description: Tese regal flowers flaunt large, scented blooms and a dazzling array of forms that resemble everything from fried egges to ballet skirts.

fields.name: Poppy
fields.description: With tissue paper petals and skinny, tendril-like stems, poppies are so ethereal, they seem to practically float on air.

fields.name: Ranunculus
fields.description: Ranunculus, which resemble small garden roses, have abundant layers of papery petal and feathery foliage.

fields.name: Rose
fields.description: Rose are everywhere. Standard varieties can be found at supermarkets across the country and are bred for shelf life and size.

fields.name: Scabiosa
fields.description: Scabiosa is a little flower that is near and dear to our hearts.

fields.name: Garden Stock
fields.description: With a strong, spicy fragrance and colorful blooms, it's hard to believe that stock shares a family with the likes of broccoli and califlower.

fields.name: Succulent
fields.description: The term "succulent" is used to describe any number of tenacious, water-retaining plants whose strong constitutions allow then to thrive in otherwise unfavorable conditions, such as poor soil and arid surroundings.

fields.name: Sunflower
fields.description: A sunflower's new buds will move their heads throughout the day in order to follow the sun, making this member of the daisy family a true sun worshipper.

fields.name: Sweet Pea
fields.description: These sweetly scented old-fashioned favorites are perfect for adding a delicate accent to large focal blooms.

fields.name: Tulip
fields.description: These spring beauties can sometimes be difficult to work with because of their bendy stems and ever-changing shape.

fields.name: Zinnia
fields.description: In the garden, zinnias are a favorite of butterflies and hummingbirds, but indoors they find just as many admirers.

fields.description: Stunning Delphium, Tulip, Rose and Tistle are a timeless combination that are sure to bring a smile.
